description:
Going by the PNW Moths description http://pnwmoths.biol.wwu.edu/browse/family-noctuidae/subfamily-noctuinae/tribe-hadenini/anarta/anarta-fusculenta/ looks to be this species, noticeable large dark claviform spot, elongate oval orbicular, and reniform spot poorly defined with some dark smoky coloration in posterior half.  The W mark on the white subterminal line quite a striking feature.

Per MPG Anarta crotchii not occurring south of Yosemite in California http://mothphotographersgroup.msstate.edu/species.php?hodges=10233.1

A nice example on BG here https://bugguide.net/node/view/642211/bgimage

Mustelin (2006) states for A. fusculenta "a relatively common and sometimes abundant species in late April –May in the mountains of southern California, particularly in the Laguna Mountains of San Diego County."

description: Garden bug. One of my kids said it was an “oil bug”. It fell into this little bowl and couldn’t get out, which is where we found it. Tucked in some tall grass by the side of our playhouse.  In the photos you can see it’s really tiny wing cases. In one of the photos it’s wings seem to be unfolding. It used its middle legs to comb the wings, I think to get them to open. it was also arching all its legs and body backwards and holding that posture, kind of like bug yoga. I don’t know why, maybe also helpful in opening the wings. Seems to have really good eyesight. When I get close with my fingers it leaps into a defensive display, arcing abdomen upwards and opening its jaws. We think if we touch it, the abdomen will spray us with something gross
